Phase 6 — Order cancellation
Service: order-service · PostgreSQL `orders` db, calling catalog-service
over gRPC (ReleaseStock)

Purely additive on top of Phase 5 — placing an order (POST /api/orders)
is untouched. This phase adds one new state transition on rows that
already exist.

Scenarios covered: 21, 22, 23.

---

## POST /api/orders/{id}/cancel

Scenario 21 (happy path), 22 (rejected attempts).

Server-side flow: gRPC CatalogService.ReleaseStock for each line item
(ORD-012, restores the quantities regardless of the product's current
status — see Archive/Development/Database §2.3), then update the order's
status to CANCELLED, then publish `order.cancelled` to RabbitMQ after
commit (Phase 7 picks this up).

Request (Alice cancels her own Placed order):
```json
POST /api/orders/20000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001/cancel
Authorization: Bearer <jwt for Alice>
```

Response — 200 OK:
```json
{
  "id": "20000000-0000-4000-8000-000000000001",
  "status": "CANCELLED",
  "updatedAt": "2026-07-13T15:00:00Z"
}
```

Response — 409 Conflict (scenario 22a, ORD-011 — cancelling an order
that's already Cancelled):
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "ORDER_NOT_CANCELLABLE",
    "message": "This order is CANCELLED and cannot be cancelled again."
  }
}
```

Response — 404 Not Found (scenario 22b, ORD-011 — cancelling an order
that isn't the caller's; same reasoning as Phase 5's GET /api/orders/{id},
existence isn't confirmed to someone who doesn't own it):
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "ORDER_NOT_FOUND",
    "message": "No order with this id."
  }
}
```

